               Dearest Madam,             ALL our family is deeply sensible of the injuries you have received at the hands of one of it, whom You only can render in any manner worthy of the relation he stands in to us all: And if, as an act of mercy and charity, the greatest your pious heart can shew, you will be pleased to look over he past wickedness and ingratitude, and suffer yourself to be our kinswoman, you will make our the happiest family in the world: And I can engage, that Lord M. and Lady Sarah Sadleir, and Lady Betty Lawrance, and my Sister, who are all admirers of your virtues, and of your nobleness of mind, will for ever love and reverence you, and do every-thing in all our powers to make you amends for what you have suffered from Mr. Lovelace. This, Madam, our should not, however, dare to petition for, were our not assured, that he is most sincerely sorry for he past vileness to you; and that he will, on he knees, beg your pardon, and vow eternal love and honour to you.             Wherefore, <i>my dearest cousin</i> (How you will charm us all, if this agreeable style may be permitted!) for <i>all</i> our sakes, for his <i>soul</i>'s sake (You must, I am sure, be so good a lady, as to wish to save a soul!), and allow me to say, for <i>your own fame</i>'s sake, condescend to our joint requests: And if, by way of encouragement, you will but say, you will be glad to see, and to be as much known personally, as you are by fame, to Charlotte Montague, I will, in two days time from the receipt of your permission, wait upon you, <i>with</i> or <i>without</i> my sister, and receive your further commands.             Let me, <i>our dearest cousin</i> (our cannot deny our the pleasure of calling you so), let me intreat you to give me your permission for my journey to London; and put my journey to London in the power of Lord M. and of the Ladies of the family, to make you what reparation the family can make you, for the injuries which a person of the greatest merit in the world has received from one of the most audacious men in it; and you will infinitely oblige us all; and particularly her, who repeatedly presumes to style her,                                   <i>Your affectionate</i> cousin, <i>and obliged Servant,</i> CHARLOTTE MONTAGUE.                     